# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: almaty
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] The **1887 Verny earthquake** occurred on June 8 at 04:35 local time in Russian Turkestan (in present-day Kazakhstan).
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] It had an epicenter in the northern foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau mountain range, or just south of the city of Verny, then the administrative centre of Russia's Semirechye Oblast.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] This earthquake destroyed the city of Verny, killing at least 330 people.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] A moment magnitude of 7.3–7.7 and MSK 64 intensity of X (*Devastating*) has been estimated for the earthquake.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] The geological forces at play in the Turkestan region are directly related to the ongoing collision of the Indian Plate with the Eurasian Plate.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] The topography of this region is influenced by broad crustal deformation as a result of convergence along the Main Himalayan Thrust.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Before the Indian subcontinent collided with Eurasia, there were island arcs and microcontinents between the two landmasses that were also converging.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] These terranes were later accreted to Eurasia as northward-moving India closed collided with Eurasia, and are now in present-day Central Asia.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Ancient suture zones mark the boundary between these accreted terranes.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] This deformation and accretion led to the formation of the Tien Shan mountains, which are moving 7±2 mm/yr towards the south along faults running along their base.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] The region is dominated by large, north and south-dipping thrust faults along the southern edge of the Tien Shan mountains, and the northern boundary of the Tarim basin, one of them being the Aheqi Fault Zone.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] The earthquake was felt over an area of 2,000,000 km2, but severe ground effects were observed approximately for 2,000 km2.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] In the meizoseismal area, the northern foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau (part of the Tien Shan), the maximum MSK 64 intensity was evaluated at IX to X.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] In Verny, the earthquake was felt with an intensity of IX.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Based on analyzing the seismic intensity of the earthquake through isoseismal maps, the moment magnitude of this earthquake was determined to fall within the range of 7.3 and 7.8 Mw.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Thrust faulting was the cause of the earthquake, likely associated with a structure lying under the Trans-Ili Alatau mountains.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] It did not produce any surface rupture, thus classifying it as a blind thrust earthquake.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Surface evidence of faults lying under the Trans-Ili Alatau mountains are sparse and sometimes absent due to the fast erosion occurring, or do not break to the surface.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Due to the absence of surface ruptures, it is not clear if the earthquake rupture faults on the foothills or within the mountain range.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] In the meizoseismal area, large landslides merged into a single mudflow.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] In the Talgar Valley, two landslides occurred with a total estimated volume of 500 m3.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Shaking corresponded to intensity VI, causing the destruction of 265 of the 576 homes in Talgar.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] In Verny, of the 1,799 brick structures in the city, only one was left standing.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Wood-constructed buildings, however, remained intact.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Many previously intact buildings collapsed during the at least 250 aftershocks that rocked the region.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] At least 332 people were killed in the city of Verny.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Of which, 161 people died (118 of them children) in Bolshoi-Almatinskaya and Malo-Almatinskaya villages.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Fourteen people, four soldiers and ten prisoners, were killed at a barrack.
[src:almaty/1887-verny-earthquake] Landslides were triggered in the mountains, killing 154 people, 87 of them were Kyrgyz.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The **1911 Kebin earthquake**, or **Chon-Kemin earthquake**, struck Russian Turkestan on 3 January.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Registering at a moment magnitude of 8.0, it killed 452 people, destroyed more than 770 buildings (which was almost all of the city) in Almaty, Kazakhstan, and resulted in 125 miles (201 km) of surface faulting in the valleys of Chon-Kemin, Chilik and Chon-Aksu.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The Tien Shan mountains form part of the broad zone of deformation associated with the continuing collision between the Indian plate and the Eurasian plate.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] In the region around Issyk Kul, the tectonic regime is a combination of thrusting and sinistral strike-slip.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The lake is formed in a ramp basin bounded to both north and south by opposite verging thrust faults, while the major Chon-Kemin–Chilik strike-slip fault runs along the linear valleys to the north.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] In the Chong-Kemin and Chilik valleys, and on the shoreline of Issyk Kul, a complex zone of surface rupture was identified by fieldwork immediately following the earthquake.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Two main zones of rupture were noted, one complex zone along the Chon-Kemin and Chilik valleys, the other along the Chon-Aksu valley.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] This complex zone of ruptures has four main segments: the 20 km long Dzhil'-Aryk, the 62 km long Lower Chon-Kemin, south side, the 40 km long Lower Chon-Kemin, north side and the 66 km long Upper Chon-Kemin-Chilik zone.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The Dzhil'-Aryk segment shows evidence of reverse faulting on a south-dipping fault plane, with no clear evidence of lateral movement.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The sense of displacement along the rest of the near-vertical Chon-Kemin and Chilik rupture zone was dominantly of sinistral (left lateral) strike-slip with minor amounts of reverse faulting, with between one and three metres of vertical displacement.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Left-lateral displacements of up to 40 m recognised from the offset of river channels, represent cumulative displacements and no separate estimates have been obtained for the 1911 event.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] This zone has two parts: the 40 km long Chon-Aksu segment and the 34 km long Aksu segment.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Along the Chon-Aksu valley the movement was dominantly reverse in type along a 60° north-dipping reverse fault, with up to 10.5 m vertical displacement and at most 1 m horizontal displacement, from the lack of observed offset of river thalwegs.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The outcrop pattern of the Aksu segment rupture indicates a low-angle thrust, possibly steepening with depth, with a maximum vertical offset or 3–5 m, decreasing steadily to the east.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] In total about 200 km of fault surfaces ruptured, although there was no visible faulting joining the two main rupture zones.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Many landslides and rock avalanches were triggered by the earthquake and are associated with the mapped zones of surface rupture.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The two largest landslides were the Kaindy rock avalanche and the Ananevo rockslide.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The Kaindy landslide, with a volume of 15 billion m3, was formed of a mass of limestone that buried a group of yurts and killed 38 people.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The Ananevo rockslide also had a volume of about 15 billion m3, and was formed of weathered granitic material, with a 250 m high backscarp that is still visible.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Most of the region's inhabitants lived in yurts, which are relatively resistant to earthquakes and unlikely to cause deaths even if they do collapse.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] The greatest damage and most of the casualties, including in yurts, resulted from landslides triggered by the earthquake, with 452 people killed and another 740 people injured.
[src:almaty/1911-kebin-earthquake] Nearly 1,100 houses and 4,545 yurts were destroyed by the earthquake and the resulting landslides.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The **1951 Asian Games**, officially known as the **First Asian Games** (Hindi: प्रथम एशियाई खेल), were a multi-sport event celebrated in New Delhi, India from 4 to 11 March 1951.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] A total of 489 athletes representing 11 Asian National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in 57 events from eight sports and discipline.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The Games was the successor of the Far Eastern Games and the revival of the Western Asiatic Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The 1951 Asiad were originally scheduled to be held in 1950, but postponed until 1951 due to delays in preparations.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] On 13 February 1949, the Asian Games Federation was formally established in Delhi, with Delhi unanimously announced as the first host city of the Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The games were managed by a strong Organizing Committee (see Organization below).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Countries invited included almost all the independent Asian countries of the time except Soviet Union (as they were part of the European Olympic Committees) and Vietnam, due to the political structure of those nations.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] National Stadium was the venue for all events.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The official logo of the First Asiad depicted a bright sun in red with 16 rays and a white circle in the middle of the disc of the sun and eleven rings, representing each participating nation, on a white background, symbolising peace.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Japanese athletes won the 24 gold, 21 silver, and 15 bronze medals, respectively; while the host nation India had 15 golds and 51 overall medals with most bronzes (20) and finished at second spot in a medal table.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The next Asian Games organised by India were the 1982 Asian Games, some 31 years later.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The 1951 Asian Games are considered to be a successor of a small-scale multi-sport event known as the Far Eastern Games, held in between a period of 1913 to 1938 in the different cities of Japan, Philippines, and mainland China.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The First Far Eastern Games took place in Manila, Philippines in 1913, after the efforts made by the Philippine Amateur Athletic Federation (PAAF).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] During the starting years of the 1930s, efforts were made to organize a multi-sport event to include the countries of West Asia too, this gave a birth to "Orient Championship Games", which later renamed as Western Asiatic Games before its first inception.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The scope of the Games comprised all the countries east of Suez and west of Singapore.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The First Western Asiatic Games was celebrated in Delhi in 1934 at the Irwin Amphitheater, in which four countries—Afghanistan, British India, Palestine Mandate and Ceylon—participated.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The decision was made to hold these Games once in four years at midpoint between the two successive Summer Olympics.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The 1938 Western Asiatic Games were scheduled to be held in Tel Aviv, Palestine Mandate.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] However, the Games was cancelled due to the outbreak of World War II, and abandoned until 1951 Games, which also considered as the revival of Western Asiatic Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] On 12 and 13 February 1949, a meeting was organized at the Patiala House, in Delhi, in between the representatives of nine Asian National Olympic Committees.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The framework of the meeting was set up in another meeting held on 8 August 1948 during the Second London Olympics, which was called by the Indian Olympic Committee's representative Guru Dutt Sondhi.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The meeting was chaired by Yadavindra Singh, president of the Indian Olympic Association.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] On the last day, Asian Games Federation (AGF)[b] was formalized and a draft constitution was accepted.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] HRH Yadavindra Singh and Guru Dutt Sondhi were respectively elected as the first president and the secretary of the federation.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The five charter members forming the federation were Afghanistan, Burma, India, Pakistan, and the Philippines.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The decision was made to organize the Asian Games Championships in four-year intervals since the inception of the Games in Delhi in February, 1950.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] HRH Yadavindra Singh, who also became the president of the organization committee of Games sent the formal invitation to several other Asian countries to participate in the 1950 Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Bhoot, Nariman Saugar who did much work with the stadium, and others.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The principal Executive members were: Director of Organisation Anthony de Mello; Secretary to the Director S.S.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Sequeira; Assistant Secretary Nariman S.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] An athletes' camp was settled in Delhi, modelled after the Richmond Park Camp of London, which accommodated athletes of the 1948 Summer Olympics.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The venue for the 1951 Asian Games was the Irwin Amphitheater, a multi-purpose sport complex, the same venue which had hosted the 1934 Western Asiatic Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Before the opening ceremony of the Games, the stadium was re-christened as the "National Stadium" and renovated for the facilities of different events of the Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Every event with the exception of swimming and water polo was hosted under the premises of the main stadium only, the events of swimming and water polo were organised at the adjacent swimming pool within the premises of the complex.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] DeMello and five-hundred thousand (500,000) rupees were required for the full construction, which was completed on 13 February 1933.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The stadium was named after the Lord Irwin, 30th viceroy of India and the then Secretary of State for War.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The Games featured six sports: Athletics, aquatics—broken into Diving, swimming, and water polo disciplines—basketball, cycling—road cycling and track cycling—football, and weightlifting.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The sports were broken down into 57 events.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Many member countries of Asian Games Federation requested for the inclusion of boxing as a medal sport, but due to various reasons, boxing did not make the final list for the Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Except athletics, women did not participate in any other event.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Asia of 1951" was also contested as the non-medal event.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The contingents were judged on the basis of their physical development, looks, and personality.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Parimal Roy of India won the event ahead of Mahmoud Namjoo of Iran, who won gold medal in the bantamweight category of weightlifting.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In diving, two medal events—3 m springboard and 10 m platform—were included.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] India and Iran were the only nations that achieved medals.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Thakkar won both the golds and overall India won 4 medals.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Iran bagged only one silver and one bronze.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In swimming, five nations sent their swimmers to participate in 8 events, 5 of freestyle (100 m, 400 m, 800 m, 1500 m, and 4 × 100 m relay) and one of each backstroke (100 m), breaststroke (200 m) and medley (3 × 100 m).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] After these Games, 800 m freestyle and 3 × 100 m medley relay were removed from the swimming calendar of Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Singapore bagged half of gold medals and 2 silvers, while Philippines earned half of total medals including 3 golds, India finished with 6 total medals including one gold of Sachin Nag in 100 m freestyle, which was the first gold of India in Asian Games; two nations left without any medal.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In water polo, only two teams—India and Singapore—participated.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The only match of the tournament decided the winner, in which the Indian team defeated Singapore with a goal difference of 6 to 4.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Athletics was the only sport in which all the eleven participating nations sent their athletes.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The Games featured 24 medal events for men and 9 for women.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Japanese women won all the 9 golds of their events and just lost four silvers to India and Singapore, two for each.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In men's events, again Japan achieved highest number of golds with count of 11, but here Indian athletes finished just one medal behind to Japan with 10 golds.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Toyoko Yoshino, a Japanese woman athlete, won all the golds in three throwing sports— shot put, discus throw, and javelin throw.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Lavy Pinto of India was the only man who achieved multiple gold medals, he finished at the top podium in men's 100 m and 200 m sprint running events.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In basketball, five Asian teams—Burma, India, Iran, Japan, and Philippines—participated.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In the matches, the round-robin format was employed and on the basis of final points table top three podium places were decided.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Philippines team without losing a single match topped the points table and grabbed a gold medal, Japan team finished behind it and won a silver medal, Iranian team with two wins finished third and won a bronze.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Host nation India, finished fourth with only single win over Burma, which came last without winning a single match.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Winning Japanese and Indian team on podium for medal ceremony.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In cycling, four nations—Burma, India, Iran, and Japan—sent their cyclists.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Two disciplines—road race and track race—were contested.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Track cycling included—1000 m sprint, 1000 m time trial, and 4000 team-pursuit; for road cycling, 180 km individual road race was contested.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The event was widely perceived as being dominated by Japan, who claimed 8 medals in total, including all the four golds out of 11 total overall medals and 4 golds.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Indian cyclists won all the rest 3 medals as Burma and Iran failed to achieve a single one.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In football, six Asian teams—Afghanistan, Burma, India, Indonesia, Iran, and Japan—participated.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The gold medal was won by the Indian team, who defeated Iran 1–0 in the final.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Japan defeated Afghanistan, 2–0 to win the bronze medal.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In weightlifting, seven countries participated in seven events—bantamweight (56 kg), featherweight (60 kg), lightweight (67.5 kg), middleweight (75 kg), light heavyweight (82.5 kg), middle heavyweight (90 kg), and heavyweight (+90 kg).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Iranian weightlifters dominated in all events and claimed 10 medals in total including all the golds, Singapore won two silvers, while both India and Philippines won one silver and one bronze.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1951 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport were held.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The numeral indicates the number of event finals for each sport held that day.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] On the left, the calendar lists each sport with events held during the Games, and at the right, how many gold medals were won in that sport.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] There is a key at the top of the calendar to aid the reader.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] On 4 March 1951, the First Asian Games were officially opened.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The list of the guests included— India's first President Rajendra Prasad, first Prime Minister of India Jawaharlal Nehru, cabinet members of Indian Government, diplomatic corps and representatives of participating Asian NOCs.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The National Stadium was filled with an estimated 40,000 spectators.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] A 31-gun salute was fired from the ramparts of the Purana Quila, adjacent to the National Stadium, in the honour of guests and participants of first Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] After a speech by the president of Asian Games Federation, HRH Yadavendra Singh, President Rajendra Prashad officially opened the Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Prime Minister Nehru presented his speech from which organisers of the Games adopted the official motto of the Games— "Play the game, in the spirit of the game".
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Fifteen of the Indian army's trumpeters with flags of eleven participating countries on their mastheads gave their performance.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] In an alphabetical order of English, athletes of the participating countries of the 1951 Asiad entered in the stadium with a march past, by following the custom of Olympics; India entered last as the host nation.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The Lighting of the Cauldron was done by the 1924 Olympian of India, Dalip Singh with the help of Asian Games torch, which had been lit by the sun's rays in the Red Fort.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Afterwards, Baldev Singh, a member of the Indian athletics squad, recited the athlete's oath on behalf of all competitors at the Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The 1951 Asiad featured athletes representing 11 National Olympic Committees.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The Organising Committee of the Games sent the formal invitations to almost all the Asian countries.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] China was invited, but did not respond before the closing dates for entries.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Pakistan declined to participate because of the Kashmir conflict with India.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] South Korea attended the meeting of Olympic representatives of Asian countries, held on 8 August 1948, during the London Olympics and agreed to send athletes for Games to participate but did not send any because of the Korean War.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The Soviet Union and Vietnam were not invited because of their political systems.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Japan was neither invited to the 1948 Summer Olympics nor to attend the founding meeting of Asian Games Federation held in February 1949 in Delhi, but allowed to participate in these Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Japan sent a 72-member strong team, the second largest after the host, and participated in all except aquatics events.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Burma and India sent their contingents in all the events.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Iran participated in all events, but did not send any female athletes.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Athletes from eight participating NOCs won at least one medal, five of them winning at least one gold medal.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Athletes from Japan earned the highest number of gold medals (24) and the most overall medals (60).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Host nation India finished second with 15 golds and 51 overall medals as well as the most bronzes (20).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Through 2010, it would be the best rank achieved by India in medal table in all succeeding Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Iran finished third with 8 golds and 16 overall medals.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Three NOCs, Afghanistan, Nepal, and Thailand failed to earn any medals.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] Singaporean swimmer Neo Chwee Kok earned the honour of winning the first gold medal in the history of the Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] He won a total of four golds, all in the free style events (400m, 800m, 1500m, and 4 × 100m relay); becoming the most medalled athlete in this Games.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The ranking in this table is consistent with International Olympic Committee convention in its published medal tables.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a nation is an entity represented by a National Olympic Committee).
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next, and then the number of bronze medals.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] If nations are still tied, equal ranking is given; they are listed alphabetically by IOC country code.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] A total of 169 medals (57 gold, 57 silver and 55 bronze) were awarded.
[src:almaty/1951-asian-games] The total number of bronze medals is less than the total number of gold or silver medals because bronze medals were not awarded in water polo and the team pursuit event of track cycling.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The **1954 Asian Games** (Filipino: *Palarong Asyano 1954*), officially known as the **Second Asian Games** – **Manila 1954**, were a multi-sport event held in Manila, Philippines, from May 1 to 9, 1954.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] A total of 970 athletes from 19 Asian National Olympic Committees (NOCs) competed in 76 events from eight sports.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The number of participating NOCs and athletes were larger than the previous Asian Games held in New Delhi in 1951.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] This edition of the games has a different twist where it did not implement a medal tally system to determine the overall champion but a pointing system.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The pointing system is a complex system where each athlete were given points according to their achievement like position in athletics or in swimming.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] In the end the pointing system showed to be worthless as it simply ranked the nations the same way in the medal tally system.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The pointing system was not implemented in future games ever since.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] Vargas was the head of the Philippine Amateur Athletic Federation (now known as Philippine Olympic Committee since 1976) and the Manila Asian Games Organizing Committee.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] With the second-place finish of the Philippines, only around 9,000 spectators attended the closing ceremony at the Rizal Memorial Stadium.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The events were broadcast on radio live at DZRH and DZAQ-TV ABS-3 on delayed telecast.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The Games were formally opened by President Ramon Magsaysay on May 1, 1954, at 16:02 local time.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] Around 20,000 spectators filled the Rizal Memorial Stadium in Malate, Manila, for the opening ceremony.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] As requested by the IOC, the torch relay and lighting of the cauldron were excluded from the Opening Ceremony to preserve the tradition of the Olympic Games.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The torch ceremony were returned at the 1958 Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The host however gave a solution by giving a special citation to the last athlete to enter the parade.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The Philippines, as host, was the last country to enter the stadium.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The flag bearer for the Philippines squad was Andres Franco, who won a gold medal in the 1951 Asian Games in high jump event, the sole gold medal of any Filipino in the athletics events of the previous Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The 1954 Asian Games featured eight sports divided into 10 events, aquatics included three events namely diving, swimming and water polo.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] This version of the Asian Games comprised more sports and events than the last one, as six sports and seven events were in the calendar of 1951 Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] Three sports—boxing, shooting and wrestling—made their debut, while cycling was dropped out.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] National Olympic Committees (NOCs) are named and arranged according to their official IOC country codes and designations at the time.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1954 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] Japan led the medal table, athletes from Japan won most medals, including most gold, silver and bronze.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] Host nation, Philippines finished second with 45 total medals (including 14 gold).
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:almaty/1954-asian-games] The host nation, Philippines, is highlighted.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The **1958 Asian Games**, officially the **Third Asian Games** (Japanese: 第3回アジア競技大会) and commonly known as **Tokyo 1958** (Japanese: 東京1958), were a multi-sport event held in Tokyo, Japan, from 24 May to 1 June 1958.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] It was governed by the Asian Games Federation.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] A total of 1,820 athletes representing 20 Asian National Olympic Committees (NOCs) participated in the Games.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The program featured competitions in 13 different sports encompassing 97 events, including four non-Olympic sports, judo, table tennis, tennis and volleyball.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Four of these competition sports – field hockey, table tennis, tennis and volleyball – were introduced for the first time in the Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] This is the first time that Japan hosted the Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The Asian Games is a multi-sport event, much like the Summer Olympics (albeit on a much smaller scale), with participation exclusively for Asian countries.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The first edition was held in the capital city of India, New Delhi, in 1951, attracting 489 competitors from 11 nations.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The programme for the Tokyo 1958 Games included 13 different sports divided into 97 events.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Four of these sports – judo, table tennis, tennis and volleyball – were not on the official Olympic sports programme at that time.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Badminton was added as a demonstration sport, which, from 1962 onwards, became a regular competitive sport in the Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The tradition of torch relay, inspired by the Olympic Games, was introduced for the first time in the Asian Games in 1958.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The relay officially began from the main venue of the Second Asian Games, Rizal Memorial Coliseum, in Manila, Philippines.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] In the host nation, Japan, it was relayed from Okinawa to Kyushu Island.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Okinawa was under the United States administration at that time.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] At the opening ceremony, the Games cauldron was ignited by the first Japanese Olympic gold medallist and the first Asian Olympic champion in an individual event, Mikio Oda.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] A record total of 1,820 athletes representing 20 member nations of the Asian Games Federation participated in the Games.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The number of participating countries was also greatest in comparison to the first two editions of the Games.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The Thai delegation held a meeting on 22 May 1958 in Tokyo, and invitations were sent to the representatives of Malaysia, Burma and Laos.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The agenda of the meeting was to discuss the possibility of forming a regional multi-sport event on the lines of Asian Games for the countries of Southeast Asia.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] This way the Southeast Asian Peninsular Games (SEAP Games), which later became the Southeast Asian Games, were established and the first SEAP Games were held in Bangkok, Thailand, in 1959.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The opening ceremony of the Tokyo 1958 Games was organised on 24 May 1958 at the National Olympic Stadium.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The ceremony, among other dignitaries and guests, included the Emperor of Japan Hirohito, crown prince Akihito and Shah of Iran Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Around 70,000 people attended the opening ceremony.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] In the following calendar for the 1958 Asian Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Athletes from 16 countries won medals, leaving four countries without a medal, and 11 of them won at least one gold medal.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] Afghanistan, Cambodia, Nepal and North Borneo did not win any medal.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The Japanese 4 × 100 metres medley relay team of Keiji Hase (backstroke), Masaru Furukawa (breaststroke), Manabu Koga (freestyle) and Takashi Ishimoto (butterfly) won the gold medal with a time of 4:17.2 and broke the world record.
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] By default, the table is ordered by the number of gold medals the athletes from a nation have won (in this context, a nation is an entity represented by a NOC).
[src:almaty/1958-asian-games] The number of silver medals is taken into consideration next, followed by the number of bronze medals.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The **1962 Asian Games** (Indonesian: *Pesta Olahraga Asia 1962*) also known as the **4th Asian Games**, **IV Asiad**, and **Jakarta 1962**, were the fourth edition of pan-Asian multi-sport event sanctioned by the Asian Games Federation (AGF).
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The games were held from 24 August to 4 September 1962, in Jakarta, Indonesia.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] It was the first international multi-sport event hosted by the then-17-year-old Southeast Asian country.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] This was the first of two Asian Games hosted by the city: the second was held in 2018, with Palembang as the co-host.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Israel and the Republic of China (ROC) were excluded from the Games, as in solidarity with People's Republic of China and fellow-Muslim majority countries in the Middle East, Indonesian immigration officials refused to issue entry visas for the Israeli and Taiwanese delegations.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] It was a breach of the rules of the AGF, and Indonesia's own promise to invite all AGF members, including those with whom it had no diplomatic relations (Israel and Republic Of China).
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] As a result, Indonesia was suspended from the International Olympic Committee, and were subsequently excluded from the 1964 Summer Olympics.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Indonesia responded to this punishment by hosting the Games of the New Emerging Forces in 1963.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] A total number of 1,460 athletes, coming from 17 countries, competed in this Asiad, where badminton made its debut.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] On 23 May 1958, voting for the 1962 host took place in Tokyo, Japan, before the 1958 Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The Asian Games Federation council voted 22–20 in favour of the Indonesian capital over Pakistani city of Karachi, the only other candidate.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Indonesia, only recently out from the shackles of colonialism, saw the fourth Asian games as its national pride.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Keeping this principle in mind, it acquired a loan of 12.5 million US dollars from Russia.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] With the help of Russian experts, a giant stadium was built, which could accommodate 100,000 spectators.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Jakarta was renovated, and the efforts at renewal included complete removal of beggars and prostitutes.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Indonesian pride was so high at that time, that it did not invite Israel and Taiwan despite both being members of the Asian Games Federation [AGF].
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] All but three official sports were held inside or around the Gelora Bung Karno Sports Complex, temporarily called the Asian Games Complex.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The shooting event was held in Cibubur Shooting Range, in what is now lies within East Jakarta.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The weightlifting and wrestling events were held at Ikada Sports Hall, now demolished to make way for the National Monument.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The nearby Ikada Stadium was also used for football event, as well as Tebet football pitch, located southeast of the complex.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The archery demonstration event was held at Menteng Stadium.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] While Weightlifting was in the program, the IWF withdrew recognition of the Asian Games competition after the Indonesian federation barred Taiwan and Israel from taking part.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] Athletes from 15 nations competed at the Asian Games.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The host nation, Indonesia, is highlighted.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] In Indonesia, a television station TVRI was established by the Indonesian government to broadcast the games for the general public, which was the first in the country.
[src:almaty/1962-asian-games] The station would become the main channel of TVRI network; and its first airdate, which coincides with the opening ceremony, become the network's founding date.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] The **1966 Asian Games**, also known as the **V Asiad** or **Bangkok 1966**, were a continental multi-sport event that was held from 9 to 20 December 1966, in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] A total of 142 events in 16 sports were contested by athletes during the games.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] Taiwan and Israel returned to the Asian Games, reversing the decision taken by Indonesia in the previous Asiad to debar the two countries.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] A total number of 2,500 athletes and officials from 18 countries, were involved in this Asiad.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] The 5th Asiad was the first one where women's volleyball was played.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] Japan led the medal table for the fifth consecutive time, and they gained a new record for the most gold medals in a single Asian Games since 1962 in Jakarta.
[src:almaty/1966-asian-games] The host nation, Thailand, is highlighted.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is in the foothills of the Trans-Ili Alatau mountains in southern Kazakhstan, near the border with Kyrgyzstan, at an elevation of 700–900 metres (2,300–3,000 feet), with the Big Almaty and Small Almaty rivers running through it.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty is the second-largest city in Central Asia and the fourth-largest in the Commonwealth of Independent States.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty was the capital of Kazakhstan from 1929 to 1991 (during the Soviet era) and after independence from 1991 until the capital was moved to Akmola (now Astana) in 1997.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is classified as a city of republican significance.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty has hosted international events, including the Alma-Ata Primary Healthcare Conference in 1978, the 2011 Asian Winter Games, and the 2017 Winter Universiade.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city was also a contender to host the 2022 Winter Olympics, but ultimately lost the bid to Beijing.
[src:almaty/almaty] It has been a UNESCO Creative City of Music since 2017, and classified as a Gamma + level global city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:almaty/almaty] Landmarks and attractions in Almaty include the Central State Museum of Kazakhstan; Ascension Cathedral; Green Bazaar; Arbat, a pedestrian area; and Kök Töbe, a hilltop recreation area with views of the city and the surrounding mountains.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city is also home to educational institutions such as Al-Farabi Kazakh National University, the Kazakh-British Technical University, the International Information Technology University, and Narxoz University.
[src:almaty/almaty] From 1929 to 1936, the city, then known as Alma-Ata, was the capital of the Kazakh ASSR.
[src:almaty/almaty] From 1936 to 1991, Alma-Ata was the capital of the Kazakh SSR.
[src:almaty/almaty] After Kazakhstan became independent in 1991, the city was renamed Almaty in 1993 and continued as the capital until 1997, when the capital was moved to Akmola (renamed Astana in 1998, Nur-Sultan in 2019, and again Astana in 2022).
[src:almaty/almaty] Since then Almaty has been referred to as the "southern capital" of Kazakhstan, whose largest and most ethnically diverse city it remains.
[src:almaty/almaty] The name *Almaty* has its roots in the medieval settlement *Almatau*, that existed near the present-day city.
[src:almaty/almaty] A disputed theory holds that the name is derived from the Kazakh word for 'apple' (алма), and is often translated as "full of apples".
[src:almaty/almaty] "Its former name, Alma-Ata, translates to 'father of the apples'".
[src:almaty/almaty] Its current name could be a pluralization of a Turkic word for "father".
[src:almaty/almaty] It is mentioned in the 16th-century *Bāburnāma* under the spelling *Almatu* (Chagatay: الماتو).
[src:almaty/almaty] Its past name was Almatau, meaning 'Apple Mountain'.
[src:almaty/almaty] There is genetic diversity among the wild apples in the Almaty region; the region west of the Tian Shan mountains is thought to be the apple's ancestral home.
[src:almaty/almaty] Nikolay Vavilov suggested the *Malus sieversii* is a candidate for the ancestor of the modern domestic apple.
[src:almaty/almaty] During 1000–900 BC in the Bronze Age, the first farmers and cattle-breeders established settlements in the territory of Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] The most famous archaeological finds have been "The Golden Man", also known as "The Golden Warrior", from the Issyk Kurgan; the Zhalauly treasure, the Kargaly diadem, and the Zhetysu arts bronzes (boilers and altars).
[src:almaty/almaty] During the period of Saka and Wusun governance, Almaty became an early education center.
[src:almaty/almaty] The region comprising modern Almaty and its surroundings was ruled by the Qara Khitai during the 12th century until they were invaded by the Mongol empire in 1218.
[src:almaty/almaty] It remained under the Mongols until the disintegration of the empire at the end of the century after which the region continued to be a part of the subsequent Chagatai Khanate, or later the breakaway Moghulistan.
[src:almaty/almaty] This region was an important trade route between the West and East, with cities like Taraz to the west and Almaliq to the east as major stopping points.
[src:almaty/almaty] The importance declined during the 15th century though, due to Temür’s attacks and him shifting the trade routes southwards, whereafter Tarim basin became the centre for Moghulistan.
[src:almaty/almaty] Wars with Timur, Bukhara Khanate and Kazakh Khanate decreased Moghul’s rule in Transoxonia over the 15th century and by early 16th century, the Almaty region came under the Kazakh rule.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Dzungar invaded, dominating the Kazakh people for a period.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Kazakhs fought to protect their land and preserve independence.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1730 the Kazakh defeated the Dzungar in the Anyrakay mountains, 70 kilometres (45 miles) northwest of Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Senior Kazakh Horde (Uly Zhuz) held jurisdiction over the region.
[src:almaty/almaty] During the eighteenth century, the city and region were near the border of the Khanate of Kokand.
[src:almaty/almaty] It was then absorbed as part of the Russian Empire in the 1850s.
[src:almaty/almaty] To establish its control of the region, Russia built **Fort Zailiyskoe** (Russian: Заилийское) between the Bolshaya and Malenkaya Almatinka rivers.
[src:almaty/almaty] Construction began on 4 February 1854 and was largely completed by autumn.
[src:almaty/almaty] The fort was a pentagonal wooden palisade with one side built along the Malaya Almatinka.
[src:almaty/almaty] Before the end of the year, it was renamed **Fort Vernoe** (Верное, "Loyal"), sometimes rendered as Vyernoe at the time.
[src:almaty/almaty] The palisade was eventually replaced with a brick wall with embrasures.
[src:almaty/almaty] The fort's main facilities were erected around the large central square for training and parading.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1867, the settlement around the fort was so large it was reorganized as the town of **Almatinsk** (Алматинск).
[src:almaty/almaty] Before the end of the year, this was renamed **Verny** (Верный, *Vernyj*).
[src:almaty/almaty] On 28 May 1887, at 4 a.m., an earthquake narrowly destroyed Verny in 11–12 minutes.
[src:almaty/almaty] By 1906, the population of the city had grown to 27,000, two-thirds of whom were Russians and Ukrainians.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 3 January 1911, the city was almost completely destroyed with over 770 brick buildings collapsing as a result of the 1911 Kebin earthquake.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1918 following the Russian Revolution and the establishment of the Bolshevik government, Soviet power was established in Verny.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city and the region became part of the Turkestan Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic (RSFSR).
[src:almaty/almaty] On 5 February 1921, Verny was renamed Alma-Ata, one of the city's ancient names, by a joint consultation of regional government representatives, professional trade associations, and local faith-based groups.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1926, the Council of Labor and Defence approved the construction of the Turkestan–Siberia Railway that was a crucial element of the future growth of Kazakhstan, especially in the east and southeast of the region.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Turkestan–Siberia Railway construction had a decisive economic impact that influenced the destiny of Alma-Ata as the capital of the Kazakh ASSR.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1930, the construction of the highway and railway to Alma-Ata was completed.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 29 April 1927, the government decided to transfer the capital of the Kazakh Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic from Kyzyl-Orda to Alma-Ata, within the RFSFR.
[src:almaty/almaty] This attracted more trade and people working with the government, stimulating intensive development in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 31 January 1928, Leon Trotsky, leader of the 1917 October Revolution, accompanied by his wife Natalia Sedova and his son Lev Sedov, was exiled to Alma-Ata by Joseph Stalin, then head of the All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks) in Moscow.
[src:almaty/almaty] Trotsky was expelled from Alma-Ata to Turkey in February 1929 and went into exile in Mexico City.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Alma-Ata airport was opened in 1930, opening up a connection from Alma-Ata to Moscow, the center of the Soviet government.
[src:almaty/almaty] Alma-Ata became the main entry by air to Kazakhstan, a status which it retains today.
[src:almaty/almaty] Transformation of this small town into the capital of the Kazakh SSR was accelerated by the large-scale construction of new administrative and government facilities and housing.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Great Purge of 1936–38 extended to Kazakhstan, where numerous people were killed.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Soviet government dominated the population.
[src:almaty/almaty] During the 1930s Kazakh nomads suffered starvation after disruption of their traditional living patterns.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1936 the Architecture and Planning Bureau developed a plan to enhance Alma-Ata as the new cultural capital of the Kazakh SSR.
[src:almaty/almaty] The plan was based on the existing rectangular system of districts.
[src:almaty/almaty] They are to be strengthened and reconstructed.
[src:almaty/almaty] During World War II the government affected the city's population and structures.
[src:almaty/almaty] To better organize the home front and concentrate industrial and material resources, the government evacuated 26,000 people and numerous industries from the European theatre of war.
[src:almaty/almaty] Alma-Ata hosted over 30 industrial facilities removed from the European section of the USSR, eight evacuated hospitals, 15 institutes, universities and technical schools; and around 20 cultural institutions.
[src:almaty/almaty] Motion picture production companies from Leningrad, Kyiv, and Moscow were also moved to Alma-Ata at this time.
[src:almaty/almaty] This brought in so many ethnic Russians that the Kazakhs became a minority in the region.
[src:almaty/almaty] In connection with the formation of the Polish Anders' Army, a Polish diplomatic post was located in the city from October 1941 to July 1942.
[src:almaty/almaty] During the years 1941–1945, industrial development increased during the postwar years.
[src:almaty/almaty] By 1967 the city had 145 enterprises, with the bulk of these being light and food industries.
[src:almaty/almaty] The main industries in Alma-Ata were: food processing (36% of gross industrial output), light industry (31%), and heavy industry (33%).
[src:almaty/almaty] From 1966 to 1971, 1,400,000 square metres of public and cooperative housing were built.
[src:almaty/almaty] Annually, around 300,000 square metres of dwellings were under construction.
[src:almaty/almaty] Most of the buildings constructed during this time were earthquake-proof multi-story buildings.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Soviet government tried to diversify architectural forms to create a more varied cityscape.
[src:almaty/almaty] During this period, many schools, hospitals, cultural, and entertainment facilities were constructed, including Lenin's Palace, the Kazakhstan Hotel, and the Medeo Sports Complex.
[src:almaty/almaty] The supersonic transport Tupolev Tu-144 went into service on 26 December 1975, carrying mail and freight between Moscow and Alma-Ata in preparation for passenger services; these began in November 1977.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Aeroflot flight on 1 June 1978 was the 55th and last scheduled passenger flight of the Tu-144.
[src:almaty/almaty] Alma-Ata was the host city for a 1978 international conference on Primary Health Care.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Alma Ata Declaration was adopted, marking a paradigm shift in global public health.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 16 December 1986, the Jeltoqsan riot took place in the Brezhnev Square (now Republic Square) in response to General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev's dismissal of Dinmukhamed Kunayev.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 7 September 1988, the subway Almaty Metro project began construction, and the subway was opened on 1 December 2011 after 23 years.
[src:almaty/almaty] Kazakhstan declared its independence from the Soviet Union on 16 December 1991 (Kazakhstan Independence Day).
[src:almaty/almaty] On 28 January 1993, the government renamed the city from the Russian *Alma-Ata* to the Kazakh name *Almaty*.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1997 the President of the Republic of Kazakhstan Nursultan Nazarbayev approved the decree to transfer the capital from Almaty to Astana in the north of the country.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 1 July 1998 a law was passed to establish the special status of Almaty as a scientific, cultural, historical, financial, and industrial centre.
[src:almaty/almaty] The new general plan of Almaty for 2030 was released in 1998.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is intended to create ecologically safe and socially comfortable living conditions in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] The main objective is to promote Almaty's image as a garden-city.
[src:almaty/almaty] It proposes continued multi-storied and single-housing development, reorganization of industrial districts or territories, improving transport infrastructure, and expanding the Almaty Metro.
[src:almaty/almaty] The first line of the Almaty metro was launched on 1 December 2011, two weeks ahead of schedule.
[src:almaty/almaty] The extension of the line to Qalqaman was opened in 2015.
[src:almaty/almaty] Nevertheless, Almaty has developed a major problem with air pollution.
[src:almaty/almaty] Already in 1995, particulate emissions, then from the city's thermal power station, exceeded Kazakh and EU standards by over 20 times.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 2008, Almaty was ranked the 9th most polluted city in the world.
[src:almaty/almaty] An independent local air quality monitoring system with a mobile app was launched in 2017.
[src:almaty/almaty] The area of the city has been expanded during recent years with the annexation of the suburban settlements of Kalkaman, Kok Tobe, Gorniy Gigant District (Mountain Giant).
[src:almaty/almaty] Numerous apartment blocks and office skyscrapers have transformed the face of the town, which has been built into the mountains.
[src:almaty/almaty] Squatter settlements such as Shanyrak have resisted eviction in the face of these development plans.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty was the site of a notorious terrorist attack in July 2016, when Jihadist Ruslan Kulikbayev killed eight police officers and two civilians in a shootout and car chase.
[src:almaty/almaty] Kulikbayev was wounded during the shootout and later sentenced to death for the attack.
[src:almaty/almaty] In March 2020, the first cases of COVID-19 were reported in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] Soon, Almaty was transformed, as the pandemic led the city into a changed behavior.
[src:almaty/almaty] The government imposed lockdowns of most institutions.
[src:almaty/almaty] In January 2022, Almaty was plunged into unrest as part of a national political crisis.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty is located in south-eastern Kazakhstan, almost 1000 km from the capital Astana.
[src:almaty/almaty] Kyrgyzstan's capital Bishkek is 190 km to the west, while Ürümqi in China is almost 1000 km east.
[src:almaty/almaty] The region is also home to the Mynjylky mountain plateau, an elevated plain located at the source of the Malaya Almaatinka river at an altitude of 3000 meters above sea level.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty has a humid continental climate (Köppen climate classification: *Dfa*) with hot summers and cold winters.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is characterized by the influence of mountain–valley circulation.
[src:almaty/almaty] This is evident in the northern part of the city, located directly in the transition zone of the mountain slopes to the plains.
[src:almaty/almaty] Annual average air temperature is equal to 10 °C (50 °F), the coldest month is January, −4.7 °C (24 °F) (on average), the warmest month (July) 23.8 °C (75 °F) (on average).
[src:almaty/almaty] In average years frost starts on about 14 October and ends on about 18 April, with sustained extreme cold from about 19 December to about 23 February, a period of about 67 days.
[src:almaty/almaty] Weather with temperature above 30 °C (86 °F) is average for about 36 days a year.
[src:almaty/almaty] In the center of Almaty, like any large city, there is a heat island.
[src:almaty/almaty] Therefore, frost in the city center starts about 7 days later and finishes 3 days earlier than in the northern suburbs.
[src:almaty/almaty] Annual precipitation is about 650 to 700 mm (25.6 to 27.6 in).
[src:almaty/almaty] April and May are the wettest months, during which about a third of the city's annual precipitation is received.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is not uncommon to see snow hitting Almaty as late as the end of May, as in the last quarter century, such snowfalls were recorded on 13 May 1985, 1 May 1989, 5 May 1993 and 18 May 1998.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty sometimes experiences winter rain, even with heavy preceding snowfall and low temperatures.
[src:almaty/almaty] The most memorable winter rain took place on 16 December 1996 during a military parade to celebrate the 5th anniversary of the Independence of the Republic.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty Weather Station's GM records south-easterly wind (30%), its resistance increases during the summer (37%) and falls in winter (19%).
[src:almaty/almaty] Wind speeds exceed 15 m/s on about 15 days a year, on average.
[src:almaty/almaty] Industrially developed and populated areas in the south and southeast of Kazakhstan are situated in the zones where the maximum magnitudes of expected earthquakes are from 6.0 to 8.3 (the intensity of I0=8–10).
[src:almaty/almaty] The south seismic active zone of Kazakhstan is a part of the North Tian-Shan ridge system.
[src:almaty/almaty] The main city of Almaty is located near the Zailiski Alatau mountain base.
[src:almaty/almaty] In recorded history prior to the late 19th century, three catastrophic earthquakes are known to have taken place there.
[src:almaty/almaty] Within the past 125 years, three more strong destructive earthquakes occurred here, with centres not more than 20–130 kilometres (10–80 mi) from the current city location.
[src:almaty/almaty] Their magnitudes were 9 and 11 on the MSK scale – 64, and their centres were located within 100 kilometres (60 mi).
[src:almaty/almaty] In each of these earthquakes, the city suffered wide destruction.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Territory of the Kyrgyz State adjoins North Tian-Shan.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty was, in 2020, considered to be "Kazakhstan's cultural capital", as contemporary Almaty has a more European character due to more cafes and restaurants with outdoor seating and public green space.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty is the historical capital of intellectualism in Kazakhstan as a product of Almaty's location along the Silk Road, and because many Russian intellectuals were exiled to the region.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Abai Kazakh State Opera and Ballet Theatre has placed the city's theater scene since 1934 and was founded around a community of local performance artists.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Kasteyev State Museum of Arts was founded in 1935, is the largest museum in Kazakhstan, and has the largest collection of artworks by Kazakh classic and contemporary artists.
[src:almaty/almaty] The wild apple *Malus sieversii* is generally accepted as having first emerged in the Almaty area and figure in Almaty's culture.
[src:almaty/almaty] Theatrical art began to develop in the city of Verny a few years after the construction of the Russian fort.
[src:almaty/almaty] On 21 November 1872, the Society of Dramatic Art Lovers staged the first production in the city: A.
[src:almaty/almaty] Ostrovsky's play, "Stay in Your Own Sled".
[src:almaty/almaty] Later, plays were performed at public, military, and commercial gatherings.
[src:almaty/almaty] An abridgement of Glinka's opera "A Life for the Tsar" was the first opera staged in the city, by the Kolpakovsky three-year city school on 23 February 1913 at the Commercial Assembly, to commemorate the tercentenary of the Romanov dynasty.
[src:almaty/almaty] The flowering of theatrical art in the city began during the Soviet period of Alma-Ata, resulting from the transfer of the capital of the Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic from Kyzylorda to Alma-Ata.
[src:almaty/almaty] Thus, the Kazakh Drama Theater, the first Kazakh professional theater, moved to the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] In the 1930s, the Opera and Ballet Theater (1934) and the Puppet Theater (1935) were established in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] After Kazakhstan regained independence in 1991, a large number of new independent theaters appeared in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] Often these are modern youth concert venues created by enthusiasts.
[src:almaty/almaty] They face funding problems, as maintaining a permanent theater company is costly.
[src:almaty/almaty] A contribution to the study of the history of culture, ethnography of southern Kazakhs in the late 19th–20th centuries was made by Turkestan scientists and local historians, united around the scientific societies and cultural and educational institutions of Tashkent.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1874, from the private collections of travelers who visited Semirechye with a scientific and regional purpose and with the help of the local intelligentsia, a museum was first created in the city of Verny, which was later transformed into a village museum of the Semirechye Cossack Host.
[src:almaty/almaty] This date is the day of the foundation of the first museum in Semirechye.
[src:almaty/almaty] Kasteev Museum of Arts was laid by the Kazakh State Art Gallery named after T.G.
[src:almaty/almaty] Its main tasks were to collect the best works of Kazakh artists and organize their creative business trips.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1936, museums in Moscow and Leningrad (now St.
[src:almaty/almaty] Petersburg) donated a significant number of paintings, graphics, sculpture and applied art to the gallery.
[src:almaty/almaty] By the end of the 1950s, the gallery's funds numbered over 5,000 exhibits, including paintings, reproductions of works by pre-revolutionary and Soviet artists, Western European and Eastern masters of art.
[src:almaty/almaty] In the 1970s and 1980s, new buildings were built for existing museums, and new thematic museums were opened: books, musical instruments, archeology, and others.
[src:almaty/almaty] A significant contribution to the development of the museum business was the opening of the Museum of the History of Almaty, which created an association of museums in the city of Almaty and the state institution "Gylym Ordasy", which united 4 museums, which allows to systematize scientific work.
[src:almaty/almaty] The first film screening in the city of Verny took place in 1900, when the physicist K.O.
[src:almaty/almaty] On it, hand-painted glass transparencies were demonstrated with the help of an overhead projector.
[src:almaty/almaty] The film show took place on 25 January in the Pushkin Garden.
[src:almaty/almaty] In January 1911, the building of the first private cinema "Twentieth Century" was opened at the intersection of Pushkin and Gogol streets, which belonged to the entrepreneur A.
[src:almaty/almaty] For the demonstration of films, the cinema was equipped with the first power plant in the history of the city, produced by the British company "Petter", with 14 horsepower.
[src:almaty/almaty] The cinema building burned down in February 1918.
[src:almaty/almaty] Starting in the 1930s, summer cinemas began to appear in the parks of the city, which were later transformed into full-fledged cinemas.
[src:almaty/almaty] Thus, the Rodina Cinema was first opened in the Central Park in 1937.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1957, it was rebuilt from a seasonal venue into a wide-screen cinema with an auditorium for 712 seats.
[src:almaty/almaty] In another park of the city, the Park of the Federation of Soviet Republics, the Progress Cinema was opened, later renamed Alma-Ata.
[src:almaty/almaty] By the early 1990s, there were 21 cinemas in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] All cinemas were divided into first, second and third screens.
[src:almaty/almaty] The cinemas of the first screen, in which the premieres of new films took place, were "Alatau", "Tselinny" and "Arman".
[src:almaty/almaty] Film films arrived at the cinemas of the third screen in a deplorable state, with glues and cuts.
[src:almaty/almaty] That is, the quality of showing the film depended on the screening of the cinema.
[src:almaty/almaty] Cinemas in the city were single-screen, two halls were owned by the cinema centers "Kazakhstan", "Arman" and "Tselinny".
[src:almaty/almaty] In the 2000s, cinemas began to open in shopping and entertainment centers, and as a result, existing stationary cinemas began to lose popularity and close.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty generates approximately 20% of Kazakhstan's GDP (or $36 billion in 2010).
[src:almaty/almaty] The city accounts for about 20% of government revenues and 60% of bank credits.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty is also a financial center, as is considered to be a Beta-Global City as of the 2012 GaWC study.
[src:almaty/almaty] One of the industries in Almaty is finance, and its financial exports make it a large contributor to Kazakhstan's balance of payments.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty is home to Halyk Bank, which is the largest bank in Central Asia, Kaspi Bank, and other major banks.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Kazakhstan Stock Exchange is based in Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty is also developing as a regional financial and business centre (RFCA).
[src:almaty/almaty] Under construction is the 'Almaty Financial District and Esentai Park'.
[src:almaty/almaty] Gottesdiener, who designed both 7 World Trade Center in New York City and Tokyo Midtown.
[src:almaty/almaty] Its goal is to become the largest business centre in Central Asia.
[src:almaty/almaty] Esentai Tower, a 37-floor building in the park, is the tallest mixed-use building in Kazakhstan, housing offices of companies such as Ernst & Young, HSBC and Credit Suisse.
[src:almaty/almaty] The first Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Kazakhstan opened in 2013 in Esentai Tower.
[src:almaty/almaty] Media companies are concentrated in Almaty, as the media distribution industry has been growing rapidly since 2006.
[src:almaty/almaty] Major broadcasting channels KTK and NTK are based in Almaty, as are several national newspapers.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Western Europe – Western China Highway passes through Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] A new airport in Almaty expects to handle about 45 million tonnes of cargo each year.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 2010, Air Astana was headquartered in Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] Before their dissolution, Air Kazakhstan and Kazakhstan Airlines were also headquartered in Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 1854, the Tsarist government built a military fortification on the left bank of the Almaty River.
[src:almaty/almaty] The construction was supervised by Major Peremyshelsky and engineer-lieutenant Aleksandrovsky.
[src:almaty/almaty] By the autumn of the same year, construction work was completed.
[src:almaty/almaty] With their arrival, the area of Almaty began to develop rapidly, and buildings were constructed during this time including the Little Stanitsa and the Tatar Slobodka.
[src:almaty/almaty] A major earthquake in 1887 destroyed 1798 brick houses and killed 322 people.
[src:almaty/almaty] After the earthquake, numerous buildings were constructed including the House of the Regiment of Military Assembly (1908), Ascension Cathedral, the House of Public Assembly, and others.
[src:almaty/almaty] At the time, Zenkov was in charge of the construction projects of the Semirechye regional government.
[src:almaty/almaty] From 1966 to 1972, most of the buildings constructed during the era were earthquake-proof multi-story housing blocks.
[src:almaty/almaty] During this period, many schools, hospitals, cultural, and entertainment facilities were constructed in post-modernist style, including Lenin's Palace (now Palace of the Republic, 1970), Hotel Kazakhstan (1977) and the Medeu (1971).
[src:almaty/almaty] According to the city's Department of Natural Resources and Resource Use Management, as of 2007 the city had 125 fountains.
[src:almaty/almaty] Among them is the "Oriental Calendar" Fountain, whose 12 sculptural figures represent the 12 animals of the Kazakh 12-year animal cycle (similar to its Chinese counterpart).
[src:almaty/almaty] There are now more than 120 fountains in Almaty, 61 of which are communally owned.
[src:almaty/almaty] Fountains, together with an extensive irrigation ditch network, play a big role in Alma-Ata – together they create a single complex of reservoirs and watercourses of the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] Every year at the end of spring, the city celebrates the "Day of Fountains" holiday where for the first time after winter, all the city's fountains are turned on.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 2006, a new fountain was opened on Lake Sayran.
[src:almaty/almaty] Previously, the highest fountain in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) gushed from this lake – a stream of water 10 cm in diameter reached a height of 50 meters.
[src:almaty/almaty] The fountain has been closed since 2008.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Medeu is an outdoor speed skating and bandy rink.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is located in a mountain valley (Medeu Valley, or the valley of Malaya Alma-Atinka River) on the south-eastern outskirts of Almaty, Kazakhstan.
[src:almaty/almaty] Medeu sits 1,691 metres above sea level, making it one of the highest skating rinks in the world.
[src:almaty/almaty] It has 10,500 square meters of ice and utilizes a sophisticated freezing and watering system to ensure the quality of the ice.
[src:almaty/almaty] Medeu was re-built in 1972 in the gorge of the same name, 15 km from the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] "Medeo" was called "the factory of records", since 126 world records were set on the ice of a high-mountain skating rink in 33 years.
[src:almaty/almaty] The ice rink, located at an altitude of 1700 m in thin air and high quality ice, is provided by pure mountain water without admixture of salts.
[src:almaty/almaty] In addition, Above the sports complex there is a mudflow protection dam and the Shymbulak.
[src:almaty/almaty] In the 1990s, the Medeu was the venue for the Voice of Asia international music festival (Asia Dauysy).
[src:almaty/almaty] Şymbūlaq is a ski resort near Almaty, located in the upper part of the Medeu Valley in the Zailiisky Alatau mountain range, at the elevation of 2,200 metres (7,200 ft) above sea level.
[src:almaty/almaty] The resort area is about 25 kilometres (16 mi) south of Almaty city by the Medeu road.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is popular for its mild climate, a large quantity of sunny days and a great amount of snow through the winter (from November until May).
[src:almaty/almaty] The resort offers both day and night skiing.
[src:almaty/almaty] The ski resort also hold a Guinness world record for the worlds highest ski slope available for night skiing.
[src:almaty/almaty] Big Almaty Lake is a natural lake located in Trans-Ili Alatau mountains on 2511 above the sea level near Almaty (15 km South from Almaty).
[src:almaty/almaty] Like a majority of lakes in Trans-Ili Alatau, this lake formed as the result of an earthquake.
[src:almaty/almaty] The lake is a major source of drinking water for the region.
[src:almaty/almaty] People can access the lake by car (approximately 1 hour drive from the city center), bike, or hiking (approximately a half-day trip).
[src:almaty/almaty] The First President's Park is an urban park located in Almaty at the intersection of Navoi Street and Al-Farabi Avenue in the Bostandyq District.
[src:almaty/almaty] The park is broken into three main areas–the avenue, boulevard, and dendrological areas.
[src:almaty/almaty] Greenery was planted according to dendrological plan.
[src:almaty/almaty] In honor of the participation of the city of Almaty in the Olympic torch relay of the Beijing Olympic Games, approximately one hundred spruces and birches were planted.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 2011, a hundred Tien-Shan spruces were also planted.
[src:almaty/almaty] Plans include a set of water projects over an area of 9.5 hectares.
[src:almaty/almaty] An aerial tramway line connects Almaty with a popular recreation area at the top of Kök Töbe (Kazakh: Көк-төбе, which means 'Blue Hill'), a mountain just to the southeast.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city television tower, Almaty Tower, is located on the hill.
[src:almaty/almaty] It was built in between 1978 and 1983, and is 371.5 m tall.
[src:almaty/almaty] The TV tower, located at an altitude of 1000 m above sea level, is the tallest structure in Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] Its height is almost 372 m, and it sits at an elevation of 1130 m.
[src:almaty/almaty] The base of the tower is a reinforced concrete foundation in the form of a three-storey sectional basement.
[src:almaty/almaty] The barrel of the tower is a metal stepped hexahedron with a diameter of 18 m at the base, 13 and 9 m at the locations of maintenance services at heights of 146 and 252 m.
[src:almaty/almaty] The structure was built taking into account the seismic mountainous terrain and can withstand an earthquake of up to 10 points.
[src:almaty/almaty] The television tower is a complex of an operating radio and television transmitting station with a special mode of operation, therefore it is inaccessible for sightseeing tours of the city from a height.
[src:almaty/almaty] The tower, illuminated at night by powerful searchlights, is visible from almost anywhere in the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Park of 28 Panfilov Guardsmen is a major park in Almaty, Kazakhstan.
[src:almaty/almaty] The park is located in east-central Almaty in the area surrounding Zenkov Cathedral.
[src:almaty/almaty] It is dedicated to and named after the Panfilov Heroes, 28 soldiers of an Almaty infantry unit who died fighting Nazi German invaders outside of Moscow in World War II.
[src:almaty/almaty] The group takes its name from Ivan Panfilov, the General commanding the 316th division which, in spite of heavy casualties, believed at that time managed to delay the Germans' advance on the capital, buying time for the defenders of the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] An eternal flame commemorating the fallen of the Russian Civil War and the Great Patriotic War burns in front of the giant black monument of soldiers from all 15 Soviet republics.
[src:almaty/almaty] The closest airport to Almaty is Almaty International Airport located 15 kilometres (9+1⁄2 mi) northeast of the city centre.
[src:almaty/almaty] Sayran Bus Terminal provides intercity bus connections within Kazakhstan, as well as international connections to Kyrgyzstan and China and regional bus connections west of the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] Sayakhat Bus Terminal provides regional bus connections to places north and east of the city.
[src:almaty/almaty] Kazakhstan Temir Joly has two stations: Almaty-1 (located 20 minutes drive from the city center, and reserved mostly for cargo) and Almaty-2 located within the city and reserved for passengers.
[src:almaty/almaty] In 2011 the Almaty Metro opened, and a light rail line was built in 2011.
[src:almaty/almaty] A bicycle-sharing system, Almaty-bike, has been in operation since September 2016.
[src:almaty/almaty] People can buy a monthly card and ride freely.
[src:almaty/almaty] The historic bandy team Dinamo won the Soviet Championships in 1977 and 1990 and the European Cup in 1978.
[src:almaty/almaty] Bandy was introduced for the first time at the 2011 Winter Asian Games.
[src:almaty/almaty] Medeu was the main arena at the 2012 Bandy World Championship.
[src:almaty/almaty] The second arena built for the championships is an alternative field at Almaty Central Stadium.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city is now a candidate to host also the 2020 Bandy World Championship.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Federation of International Bandy has opened an office for Asia, which is located in Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty was the host of the 2017 Winter Universiade with bandy on the programme.
[src:almaty/almaty] The 2011 Asian Winter Games were held jointly in Almaty and Astana.
[src:almaty/almaty] The ice hockey and ski jumping competitions were held in the city at the Baluan Sholak Sports Palace and Sunkar International Ski Jumping Complex respectively.
[src:almaty/almaty] The biathlon, cross-country skiing, and ski orienteering competitions were held at the nearby Soldatskoe Valley Cross Country Skiing and Biathlon Stadium; the Alpine skiing and bandy competitions were held in nearby Shymbulak and Medeo respectively.
[src:almaty/almaty] The Yenbek Almaty ice hockey team played from 1965 to 1985 and from 1999 to 2009.
[src:almaty/almaty] HC Almaty plays in the Kazakhstan Hockey Championship.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city's primary football team is FC Kairat founded in 1954 and one of the most successful Kazakh clubs.
[src:almaty/almaty] The club made history by qualifying for the 2025-26 UEFA Champions League, thus becoming only the second Kazakhstani football club to do so.
[src:almaty/almaty] Futsal club AFC Kairat has won the UEFA Futsal Cup in 2012–13 and 2014–15.
[src:almaty/almaty] Basketball team BC Almaty won the 2015 and 2016 editions of the Kazakhstan Basketball Cup.
[src:almaty/almaty] Following the successful hosting of the 2011 Winter Asian Games, Almaty made a bid to host the XXII Olympic Winter Games in 2014, but was eliminated from consideration, not making the "short list" of candidate cities.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty was the 2017 Winter Universiade host.
[src:almaty/almaty] The city was exploring possible bids, such as the 2018 Winter Olympics, but did not submit one.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty submitted a bid to host the 2022 Winter Olympics in August 2013, but lost to Beijing.
[src:almaty/almaty] Almaty may still consider to submit a bid to host the 2030 Winter Olympics.
[src:almaty/almaty] The International Monetary Fund announced in October 2019 that it would launch a new regional technical assistance centre (RTAC) in Almaty.
[src:almaty/almaty] The centre will provide capacity development services to nine IMF member countries in the CCAM region.
[src:almaty/almaty] The centre is expected to cover the fiscal policy, central bank operations, financial sector supervision, and macroeconomic statistics.
